03976nam a22005175i 9780773564039DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20032003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735640397 a10.1515/97807735640392doi  a(DE-B1597)657803  a(OCoLC)732601068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR4487.R4bH33 1985eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a821/.71 aHarding, Anthony John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aColeridge and the Inspired Word /cAnthony John Harding. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v800tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tBeyond Mythology: Coleridge and the Legacy of the Enlightenment -- tBeyond Nature -- tInspiration and Freedom: The “Letters on the Inspiration of the Scriptures” -- tThe Broad Church, F. D. Maurice, and Coleridge’s “Letters on the Inspiration of the Scriptures” -- tJohn Sterling and the Universal Sense of the Divine -- tThe Divinity in Man -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis movement radically revised the interpretation of the Bible as an "inspired" book and also helped to redefine the inspiration attributed to poets, since many poets of the period, including Coleridge himself, wished to emulate the prophetic voice of biblical tradition. Coleridge's mastery of this new study and his search for a new understanding of the Bible on which to ground his faith are the focus of this book. Beginning with an exposition of Coleridge's double role as theologian and poet, Anthony Harding analyses the development and transmission of Coleridge's views of inspiration - both biblical and poetic - and provides a history of his theological and poetic ideas in their second generation, in England especially in the work of F.D. Maurice and John Sterling, and in America in that of Ralph Waldo Emerson. Harding argues that Coleridge's emphasis on the human integrity of the scriptural authors provided his contemporaries with a poetics of inspiration that seemed likely to restore to literature a "biblical" sense of the divine as a presence in the world. Coleridge's treatment of biblical inspiration is thus an important contribution to Romantic poetics as well as to biblical scholarship. His concept of inspiration is also linked directly to his literary theory and thus to the current debate over the reader's relation to text and author.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356403940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773564039423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773564039/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles